# Arrow Functions

Use `const` arrow functions instead of `function` declarations.

```typescript
// BAD
function getName(id: string): string {
  return id;
}

async function loadUser(id: string) {
  return await db.get(id);
}

export function helper() {}

// GOOD
const getName = (id: string): string => {
  return id;
};

const loadUser = async (id: string) => {
  return await db.get(id);
};

export const helper = () => {};
```

## Notes

- Prefer `const name = () => {}` / `const name = async () => {}` for module-level helpers and exports.
- Generics: `const run = async <T>(value: T): Promise<T> => value;`
- Do not convert class methods.
- Keep concise single-expression arrows when readable: `const double = (n: number) => n * 2;`
